Overview

In this homework, you will review OLS regression. The concepts focused on here are obviously not all of what you know (from STAT 350), but they are concepts that are particularly important for this course. Pay particular attention to interpretation.

Data

For this assignment, we are using the Duncan dataset. This dataset provides data on the prestige and other characteristics of 45 U. S. occupations in 1950. The data was collected by the sociologist Otis Dudley Duncan.

2. Regression Analysis

A. Model 1

Use thelm() function to fit a linear regression model to the data, in which education and income are regressed on prestige.

Interpret the findings from this model. Are education and income good explanations for an occupationâs prestige? Interpret the coefficient for income - what does it mean? Does education or income have a larger effect on prestige? Justify your conclusion.

Solution

From the output we can see that R^2 is 0.8282 and the F statistics is 101.2 with corresponding p value < 2.2e-16 hence income and education are good explanations for prestige. And their p-values are both very significant.
The coefficient for income is 0.59873 which means that at a fixed level of education, a unit of increase in income is expected to cause 0.59873 increase in prestige. It means that there is a positive relationship between prestige and income.
The coefficients for education and income are 0.54583 and 0.59873 with corresponding p-values 1.73e-06 and 1.05e-05 respectively. Although the coefficient of income is larger than that of education, the p-value of education is smaller which means education is more stable. So basically, I think they have roughly the same effect on prestige.

model1 <- lm(prestige ~ education + income, data = Duncan)
summary(model1)

B. Model 2

Now, add in the type of occupation to the model. Is the model with type a better model? Explain what statistics you would use to make this decision, conduct the analysis, and interpret the results.

Solution

Yes, model2 is a better model than model1. There are many different indices that support this conclusion. First, the adjusted R^2 of model2 is higher than that of model1. Second, by using the ANOVA, we get a very small p value which also means that model2 explains more than model1. Third, by checking the AIC and BIC, we can see that these two indices of model2 are lower that that of model1 which also proves the conclusion.

model2 <- lm(prestige ~ education + income + type, data = Duncan)
summary(model2)

3. Regression Diagnostics

A. Non-normality

The rstudent() function returns studentized residuals, and the densityPlot() function fits an adaptive kernel density estimator to the distribution of the studentized residuals. A qqPlot() can be used as a check for nonnormal errors, comparing the studentized residuals to a t-distribution.

Use these to examine the results of your best model from Question 2. What do you conclude?

Solution

From the Kernel Density Plot of Studentized Residuals, we can see that it roughly follows a t distribution. But we can also see there is a heavy right tail indicating positive skewness.
From the QQ-plot, we can see that the studentized residuals are align with t distribution with machinist and minister two outliers.
Therefore we can say that model2 is indeed a nice model but we can pay more attention to the positive skewness and outliers problem for further interest.

studentized_residuals <- rstudent(model2)
densityPlot(studentized_residuals,
            main = "Kernel Density Plot of Studentized Residuals",
            xlab = "Studentized Residuals")
qqPlot(studentized_residuals, 
       distribution = "t", 
       df = 40,
       main = "Q-Q Plot of Studentized Residuals",
       xlab = "Theoretical Quantiles (t-distribution)", 
       ylab = "Studentized Residuals")
 minister machinist 
        6        28

B. Influence = outliers * leverage

The outlierTest() function tests for outliers in the regression. The influenceIndexPlot() function creates a graph that displays influence measures in index plots. The avPlots() function creates added variable plots, which allow you to visualize how influential data points might be affecting (or not) the estimated coefficients.

Using these (and/or other tools), using your preferred model from Question 2, are there any influential data points?

If the diagnostics suggest that there are influential points, does removing these influential points change the results of the analysis? Compare models using the compareCoefs() function. What do you conclude?

Solution

From the outputs we can see that minister is definitely a influential data point and an outlier based on cookâs distance, leverage and other indices. Machinist is also a influential data point since it is away from other datapoints in terms of studentized residuals and Bonferroni p-value. It is not as extreme as minister but it it also worth attention. RR.enigeeer is also an influential data point since it has high leverage value but not an outlier. From the added variable plots, we can also observe that machinist and minister are away from other data points in all four plots. Therefore, if we remove influential points, we should remove minister and machinist.

After removing minister and machinist, we observe that all coefficients are affected by the removal of these two data points, with changes in different directions. Additionally, the standard errors of all coefficients decreased, indicating that the removal of these two influential points made the model more stable and improved the precision of the coefficient estimates.

outlier_test <- outlierTest(model2)  
print(outlier_test)
         rstudent unadjusted p-value Bonferroni p
minister 3.829396         0.00045443      0.02045
influenceIndexPlot(model2, main = "Influence Index Plotand ")
avPlots(model2, main = "Added Variable Plots")
Duncan_no_minister_machinist <- Duncan[!rownames(Duncan) %in% c("minister", "machinist"), ]
model3 <- lm(prestige ~ education + income + type, data = Duncan_no_minister_machinist)
compareCoefs(model2, model3)

C. Non-linearity

Component-plus-residual plots allow for the detection of non-linearity in the partial relationship between each covariate and the outcome. These can be created using the crPlots() function.

For your preferred model, does it appear there is any nonlinearity? Explain.

Solution

From the plots we can observe that generally there is no nonlinearity, but there maybe some nonliearity at lower level of education.

crPlots(model3, main = "Component-Plus-Residual Plots for Model 3")

D. Heteroscedasticity

Non-constant error variance can be tested using the ncvTest() function.

Does it appear that this is a concern with this data? Explain

Solution

Based on the output, the p-value of 0.3534 indicates that there is no significant evidence of heteroscedasticity in the model. We can assume that the error variance is constant, and heteroscedasticity is not a concern with this data.

ncvTest(model3)
Non-constant Variance Score Test 
Variance formula: ~ fitted.values 
Chisquare = 0.8612201, Df = 1, p = 0.3534

4. Interpretation

Should the model above be used to answer a descriptive, explanatory, or predictive question? Explain your answer.

Solution

The model should be used to answer explanatory question. For descriptive questions, we need summary statistics like mean, median and variance, so this is not needed for such questions. The coefficients, test statistics, p-values are all great indices to explain the influence of the variables, hence the model is a great method for explanatory problem. For prediction problem, we have not made any explorations on its prediction accuracy like cross-validation. Therefore, it is better not to be used for prediction at this stage.
